        </tbody>
    </table>
</div>
</p>
<p>It says:</p>
<blockquote><p>Stop being fancy! Just call the setter method like normal!</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Go refresh the form, and submit!</p>
<h2 id="the-adder-and-remover-methods">The Adder and Remover Methods <a class="headerlink" href="by-reference-adder-remover#the-adder-and-remover-methods" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>Ah! It's yelling at us! This is the error we expected all along:</p>
<blockquote><p>Neither the property <code>studiedGenuses</code> nor one of the methods - and then it
lists a bunch of potential methods, including <code>setStudiedGenuses()</code> - exist
and have public access in the <code>User</code> class.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In less boring terms, the form system is trying to say:</p>
<blockquote><p>Hey! I can't set the <code>studiedGenuses</code> back onto the <code>User</code> object unless you
create one of these public methods!</p>
</blockquote>
<p>So, should we create a <code>setStudiedGenuses()</code> method like it suggested? Actually,
no. Another option is to create adder &amp; remover methods.</p>
<p>Create a <code>public function addStudiedGenus()</code> with a <code>Genus</code> argument:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="7cee6f9737">
